{
  "text": "This theorem implies that a minimum beacon set can be computed trivially and optimally for any single-arity network (one that contains only single-arity nodes), without using the \"pruning\" algorithm presented earlier. In [CITATION_1] , we show that a single-arity network is a tree. Theorem 5 lets us reduce the set of potential beacons used in Algorithm 3 to the set of high arity nodes. This can lead to substantial computational savings. For instance, we show in Section 5 (and Figure 3) , that the number and fraction of single arity nodes in current ISP topologies can be quite high.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7339641"
